AB  - Land-use change in the southern Sukabumi Regency can affect the dynamics of accessibility, food resources, tourism, and other resource management. This study analyses land-use changes and disaster exposure in 2000, 2010, and 2020 using the Storie index method. This study used multitemporal satellite imagery to process land-use maps, then calculate with precipitation data, digital elevation model, and regional soil map to process landslide potential. The result shows there was a decrease every ten years in un-similar forests (3-2%), similar forests (4-1%), and rice fields (1%). Meanwhile, the increase occurred in settlements (2%), moors (1%), and plantations (8-2%). The fluctuating area occurs in ponds and open ground with a difference of 1%. Mostly the built-up area has extended from the previous condition that coming from the agricultural area. Potential landslides occurred at the turn of the year due to the highest precipitation. Three-quarter of the study area has moderate potential for landslides, while the area with a high potential for landslides continues to increase (3-7%). Areas with a high and very high potential for landslides have steep or very steep with various land use, either moors, settlements, or open ground. © 2023 Author(s).
