AD  - Department of Geography, Faculty of Mathematics and Natural Sciences, University of Indonesia, UI Campus, Depok, 16424, Indonesia
AB  - Majalengka Regency is one of the districts with a high landslide hazard in West Java Province. They are mostly affected by heavy rainfall or prolonged rain. This study aims to classify landslide events in 2018-2019 based on physical factors consisting of slopes, soil types, lithology, land use, and vegetation density using the K-Means Clustering analysis method. To analyze the characteristics of rainfall that triggered landslides in 2018-2019 using the Thiessen polygon method. The results showed that the clustering of landslide events in 2018-2019 in Majalengka Regency was formed five clusters with the highest rainfall on the D-Day average in cluster 5, which is 49 mm/day. The highest average cumulative rainfall 3 days before the landslide events was in cluster 4, which is 80 mm/day. The highest average cumulative rainfall 5 days before the landslide events was in cluster 3 is 112 mm/day. The highest average cumulative rainfall 10 days before the landslide events was in cluster 1, which is 174 mm/day.  © 2021 Published under licence by IOP Publishing Ltd.
