TI  - Application of jute geo textiles technique for slope stabilization and regeneration of vegetation in north-western himalayas
PY  - 2016
T2  - GA 2016 - 6th Asian Regional Conference on Geosynthetics: Geosynthetics for Infrastructure Development, Proceedings
SP  - 738
EP  - 746
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85009107110&partnerID=40&md5=5ca56696cf843b951b44a54d170e016f
AD  - ICAR-Indian Institute of Soil and Water Conservation, India
AB  - Non-arable lands in India have been estimated to the extent of 107 m ha where agriculture is not possible due to inherent limitations of steep slopes, erosion hazards, stoniness/rockiness, shallowness, fl ooding and anthropogenic factors like road construction and mining. These lands range from V, VI, VII and VIII categories. Geotextile materials of various specifications are manufactured for different soil conservation applications. Bio-engineering techniques are being increasingly favoured to control soil erosion in general and slope stabilization in particular. Geo jute materials of three grades viz., 500, 600 and 700 gsm with an open mesh of 16 mm × 22 mm were applied at the landslide site in Ashti village situated at an elevation of 1600 m a.s.l. with steep slopes of about 70% (35o) situated in the middle Himalayas covering 0.65 ha. Phyto sociological studies were conducted at the three treated and control sites of the land slide. The engineering measures involved provision of a diversion drain, digging of anchor trench at upper side and anchoring of upper end of geotextiles in the trench and backfilling it. Jute geotextile (JGT) reinforced retaining walls (10 in numbers) were constructed which functioned satisfactorily. The highest IVI and visual observations showed that Bidens biternata has the maximum ability to grow on severely degraded lands and can be identified as an ecological tool in rehabilitation of degraded lands as it recorded its presence at all the four locations. After two years of application, there were differences for soil moisture and ecological parameters between the treated sites and the untreated control. Geo-jute materials with 700 gsm was found to support greater vegetation followed by 600 gsm and 500 gsm primarily due to high soil moisture at geo jute site, 700 gsm (11.9-12.5-%) whereas in control the soil moisture was 9.9 to 10.1% respectively. The best performance of JGT was recorded at Site-1 (700 gsm) followed by Site-2 (600 gsm) and lowest regeneration was recorded for grasses, herbs and shrubs at Site-3 (500 gsm) with geo-jute treatment. Geojute prevented the displacement of soil particles and also acted as mulch over the soil for better growth of natural vegetation. Species richness, Shanon index and index of dominance were the highest at site I with 700 gsm JGT material. Thus geojute textile application alongwith engineering techniques was found successful for establishment of natural vegetation on degraded slopes.
