AD  - Department of Geography, The University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC, Canada
AB  - Abstract: This chapter summarizes findings on the morphological response of Peace River and its bordering riparian vegetation to 40 years of regulated flows consequent upon the closure of W.A.C. Bennett Dam in late 1967 and draws some conclusions for long-term management of this and similar situations. The river has aggraded locally in response to sediment influx from tributaries and major landslides; it has not degraded. In the upper river, flows below the threshold for competence to move the bed material account for this outcome; in the lower river the continuing dominance of Smoky River sediment influx controls the morphological trend. Riparian vegetation has prograded onto former bar surfaces, now customarily exposed, but succession has been largely constrained to early shrub stages due to winter high water and ice damage. Ice effects have been reduced in the upper river, but are little affected in the northward flowing, lower river beyond the confluence with Smoky River. Competence calculations and the history of exceptional flows suggest that effective flushing flows should be of order 5000 m3s-1 in the upper river. This edition first published 2015 © 2015 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.
