TI  - Ecology of a woodland butterfly with near-threatened status, Sasakia charonda, (Lepidoptera, Nymphalidae) and management of riparian and secondary broadleaf deciduous forests for conservation of the butterfly
PY  - 2011
T2  - Insect Habitats: Characteristics, Diversity and Management
SP  - 1
EP  - 82
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84892197048&partnerID=40&md5=b83acf33548d6e2457c38be001bc0c08
AD  - Yamanashi Institute of Environmental Sciences, Yamanashi, Japan
AB  - To clarify forest management plan for conservation of the woodland butterfly, Sasakiacharonda, the near-threatened species in Japan, we investigated the population ecology of thebutterfly and its host trees, Celtis sinensis and Celtis jessoensis, in riparian forests and thesurrounding secondary broadleaf deciduous forests before used and managed for productionof firewood and charcoal (hereafter, secondary forests). Riparian forests regenerated by floodsand/or landslides functioned as sites for regeneration of host trees, for courting, puddling andegg laying behaviors of adult butterflies, and for habitats of the butterfly larvae. While,secondary forests located behind riparian forests functioned as sites for roosting behaviors ofadult female and for sipping tree sap by adult males. Therefore, the original habitat of S.charonda is probably a riparian forest and we found that the landscape with both riparian andsecondary forest habitats had important roles in the maintenance of the butterfly and its hosttree populations. Consequently, the recommended habitat management for conserving thebutterfly populations is the ensuring of sufficient width in riverbed for guaranteeing the eventof natural disturbances and the reductions in the construction of barriers to prevent landslidesand concrete shore embankments together with the securing of secondary forests. On the otherhand, in the habitats consisted of only secondary forests, which are considered to befunctioned as alternative habitats of S. charonda instead of riparian forests, many adult S. charonda sipped tree sap of Quercus acutissima. C. sinensis trees regenerated at the edges ofsecondary forests newly established by partial deforestation. Thus, although the partialdeforestation of secondary forests with the alteration in traditional land use decrease the totalarea of secondary forests, it created new forest edges and led to the increase in the number ofthe host trees. However, contrary to this, such deforestation led to the decrease in the densitiesof both larvae and adults of the butterfly. Thus, the habitat requirements of S. charonda and itshost trees are contrary each other. To compound these contrasting habitat requirements, it isnecessary to create new forest edges continuously in a given habitat without decreasing totalarea of secondary forests. Therefore, in secondary forest habitats, recommended managementfor conserving the butterfly populations is traditional coppicing that secondary forestscontaining stands of Q. acutissima and host trees are divided into several blocks and theseblocks are cyclically and sequentially deforested without decreasing total area of secondaryforests. © 2010 by Nova Science Publishers, Inc. All rights reserved.
