SP  - 17
EP  - 24
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0033371748&partnerID=40&md5=67983b797b0a3a3ad5b2681d947ca79b
AD  - The Rsrch. Inst. of Trpcal. Forestry, CAF, Guangzhou 510520, China
AB  - The landslide caused by No. 9508 typhoon storm at Tianchi of Hainan's Jianfengling was investigated, the root systems of regenerated tropical mountain rain forest and young Chinese fir plantation were measured, and the relations between typhoon storm, root system and landslide were analyzed in the paper. The results indicated that: (1) During the No. 9508 typhoon storm, there were more than 20 landslides of which the largest one took up 320 m2 area in the investigated 15 ha Chinese fir plantation land; however there was no landslide in the close tropical mountain rain forest land. The landslides occurred in the land with steep gradient (35°-55°). (2) The biomass of root per unit soil mass in the regenerated tropical mountain rain forest (17.72 kg/m3 soil) was 4.76 times that in young Chinese fir plantation (3.72 kg/m3 soil). (3) The root mass each root diameter (d < 0.2, 0.2 < d < 0.5, 0.5 < d < 1, and d > 1 cm) in the regenerated tropical mountain rain forest (young Chinese fir plantation) accounted for 14.0% (41.4%), 10.5% (22.4%), 28.1 (8.5%), and 47.4% (27.7%) respectively of the total root mass. (4) There were few dead roots in the regenerated tropical mountain rain forest and many dead roots (especially the large roots with diameter > 1.0 cm) in the young Chinese fir plantation. The dead root mass each root diameter (d < 0.2, 0.2 < d < 0.5, 0.5 < d < 1, and d > 1 cm) in the later forest accounted for 6.5%, 24.6%, 50.7%, and 92.9% respectively of the corresponding root class's total root mass. (5) Storms, especially typhoon storms with high rainfall and rainfall intensity was the outer factor that led to landslide, larger amounts of rainfall made soil moisture increase, soil mass soften, soil particles' coherent and friction decrease, and made shearing strength of soil decline. Also, the deforestation was an important inner factor of landslide, it caused root dead and resulted in decline and/or loss of function of soil conservation.
