AB  - After an introductory article, the special issue concentrates on the effects of Hurricane Hugo (1989) on wet forest in the Luquillo Experimental Forest, Puerto Rico. There are 15 papers: the first five years in the reorganization of aboveground biomass and nutrient use following Hurricane Hugo; the temporal scales at which disturbance affects belowground nutrient pools; litter dynamics along stream, riparian and upslope areas following Hurricane Hugo; functional diversity of soil bacterial communities in tabonuco forest; distribution and abundance of tropical freshwater shrimp along a stream corridor; disturbance influences long-term population patterns in the Puerto Rican frog Eleutherodactylus coqui; the legacy of disturbance on habitat associations of terrestrial snails; a 12-yr comparison of stand changes in a mahogany plantation and a paired natural forest of similar age; land-use dynamics in a post-agricultural Puerto Rican landscape (1936-1988); forest recovery in abandoned cattle pastures along an elevational gradient; anthropogenic disturbance of Caribbean mangrove ecosystems; ecosystem development and plant succession on landslides in the Caribbean; effects of hurricane disturbance on groundwater chemistry and riparian function; background and catastrophic tree mortality in tropical moist, wet and rain forests; and a theory of disturbance and species diversity, with evidence from Nicaragua after Hurricane Joan (1988).
