AB  - The impact of vascular plants with symbiotic nitrogen fixers on species' replacements in primary succession was examined by surveying 150 studies from the literature. Nitrogen fixers were present in 77% of all seres but were a dominant part of the vegetation in only 28%. They were most abundant on glacial moraines and mudflows, of intermediate abundance on mine tailings, landslides, floodplains, and dunes, and least abundant on volcanoes and rock outcrops. Nitrogen fixers provide the principal inputs of nitrogen but little is known about the relative magnitude of inputs and outputs in primary succession. Nitrogen fixers facilitated growth of associated species in some cases (eg mine tailings), but generalizations about their facilitative role are misleading because nitrogen fixers often compete successfully for resources with other colonizers, thereby inhibiting growth of associated species and slowing species turnover. -from Author
