AB  - The mechanism of recovery of disturbed ecosystems in the moist temperate oak forest belt in Kumaun Himalaya was studied on 7 sites at which landslides had occurred. The first plants to invade were annual forbs. Perennials then entered, and competed and shared dominance with the annuals during Years 6-13. Finally, the dominance shifted largely to perennials and the composition of the herb layer showed no perceptible change after 21 yr. The herb cover was positively related with species content. Shrubs appeared after 6 yr. After 40 yr, juvenile trees of climax species were present but sparse. Biomass accumulation in the herb layer followed an asymptotic curve which leveled off at c40 yr. A positive relationship occurred between biomass and species diversity. Biomass accumulation in the shrub layer did not follow a definite sequence. The concentrations of nutrients (N, P, K, Na, Ca and organic C) in soil increased with time, and achieved a similar concentration to that in nearby reference forest after 40 yr. Enrichment of soil nutrients showed a positive feedback relationship with plant biomass accumulation. Among the nutrients, recovery of K was fastest. The pattern of succession conformed to the tolerance model and emphasized the importance of the initial floristic composition and the local propagule reservoir.-from Authors
